Cook,<br><br>
I am impressed with your compilation of information. I really like the Nixon quote:<br><br>
&quot;No event in American history is more misunderstood than the<br>
Vietnam War. It was misreported then, and it is           misremembered now. Rarely have so many people been so wrong<br>
about so much. Never have the consequences of<br>
their misunderstanding been so tragic.&quot; [Nixon]<br><br>
That really says it all. Unfortunately, numbers and quotes really do little for me in the way of fixing my head over this.<br><br>
What I would like to see is Westmoreland explain the &quot;body count&quot; lie.<br><br>
What I would like to see is Westmoreland explain why &quot;cleared&quot; Vietnamese nationals were allowed to work in camps and blow away our buddies once in a while, at their liesure.<br><br>
What I would like to see is Westmoreland explain............<br><br>
I won't go on. <br><br>
My point is that there is another very black side to the Vietnam War that politicians and military leadership avoid at the risk of exposing other realities that would show them as the real kind of individuals they are, and where most of the real problems originated.<br><br>
I personally find these quotes outrageous:<br><br>
91% of Vietnam Veterans say they are glad they served<br>
[Westmoreland]<br><br>
74% said they would serve again even knowing the outcome<br>
[Westmoreland]<br><br>
I am proud that I did my duty for my country, and that I did the best job I could, but I find a black cloud over being &quot;glad&quot; that I was in Vietnam, and I would NEVER expose myself again to the idiocy of the procecution of that conflict. I have yet to encounter anything that would restore even the slightest confidence in the political or military leadership of that time, much less rely on their utterances for solace. <br><br>
Other than those points which you can deduce with which I have a problem, I really like your compendium and will download it for future reference.<br><br>
